SEVERE FEVER W/THROMBOCYTOPENIA SYND. - JAPAN, SOUTH KOREA: UPDATE
******************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

In this update:
[1], [2] Japan
[3] South Korea

******
[1] Japan
Date: Fri 24 May 2913
Source: Japan Daily Press (JDP) [edited]
http://japandailypress.com/researchers-finally-find-virus-carrying-tick-that-has-caused-8-deaths-2429483


For the 1st time Japanese researchers have found and identified a tick as carrying the virus that causes severe fever with thrombocytopenia syndrome (SFTS) that has so far caused 8 deaths in the country since the summer of 2012. 15 people have been infected across 10 prefectures ever since the virus was reported in the country in January 2013.

The tick was discovered in a woman in her 60s at a national medical center in Iwakuni city, western Japan. She was hospitalized in early April [2013] and had high fever and slipped in and out of consciousness. She also complained that she found it hard to breathe and was once confined to the intensive-care unit. Her doctors found a 3 millimeter tick on her arm and the researchers at the National Institute of Infectious Diseases confirmed that it carried the virus. The tick is the kind that preys on animals in the wild. This virus was first discovered in China back in 2009 but the Health Ministry confirmed that the strain found in the infected patients has genetic origins in Japan. The symptoms for SFTS usually develop within 2 weeks of the initial stage of infection. No vaccine is available at this time but the discovery of the tick might lead to one being developed in the near future.

[Byline: Ida Torres]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Kunihiko Iizuka

******
[1] Japan
Date: Wed 13 Mar 2013
Source: Japan Daily Press (JDP) [edited]
http://japandailypress.com/3-more-cases-of-tick-related-virus-identified-in-japan-1325049


The Japanese Health Ministry said this week [week of 13 Mar 2013] that it had identified 3 more cases of people infected with a mysterious tick-borne virus. This brings the total number of cases to 8, and while the 1st 5 were all deaths, these 3 people, infected between 2005 and 2012, all recovered.

The virus causes severe fever with thrombocytopenia syndrome, or SFTS, and symptoms are said to usually develop within 2 weeks [of infection]. There is no vaccine at this time. The virus was first discovered in China in 2009 and until now has been seen as transmitted by mite or tick bites. But no bite marks were found in the people in Japan who died and they had no record of recent travel outside the country. Likewise, the Health Ministry has confirmed that the strain of the virus has genetic origins from Japan, not another country. The 1st death was reported in the summer of 2012 while the others were in the fall, but the identification of the tick-related virus as the cause wasn't made until February [2013]. The Health Ministry is still looking into another 5 suspected cases.

The 3 surviving infection cases all occurred before the summer of 2012 death. The 1st was a man in his 50s from Nagasaki Prefecture who became ill in November 2005, followed by a man in his 80s in Saga Prefecture in August 2010, and a woman in her 80s in Kochi Prefecture in April 2012. The 3 were hospitalized and received treatment, eventually recovering. As the 2nd and 3rd deaths were confirmed, an official from the Health Ministry said that he believed it wasn't necessary to be concerned about the infection spreading across the country. While levels of concern should certainly be kept in check as it is obvious the virus can be treated, it is also clear that the number of identified cases is rising faster than expected.

[Byline: Adam Westlake]

--
