[Maps of South Korea can be accessed at http://www.nationsonline.org/maps/korea-south-admin-map.jpg and http://healthmap.org/r/1BIE. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]

[The characterization of the virus responsible for SFTS was described first by Yu XJ et al in a publication in the N Engl J Med. 2011 Apr 21;364(16):1523-32, entitled 'Fever with thrombocytopenia associated with a novel bunyavirus in China' (http://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMoa1010095).

Heightened surveillance of acute febrile illness in China since 2009 has led to the identification of a severe fever with thrombocytopenia syndrome (SFTS) with an unknown cause. Infection with _Anaplasma phagocytophilum_ has been suggested as a cause, but the pathogen has not been detected in most patients on laboratory testing. Yu et al obtained blood samples from patients with the case definition of SFTS in 6 provinces in China. The blood samples were used to isolate the causal pathogen by inoculation of cell culture and for detection of viral RNA on polymerase-chain-reaction assay (PCR). The pathogen was characterized by electron microscopy and nucleic acid sequencing, and enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay, indirect immunofluorescence assay, and neutralization testing were used to analyze the level of virus-specific antibody in patients' serum samples.

The novel virus was designated as SFTS bunyavirus from patients who presented with fever, thrombocytopenia, leukocytopenia, and multiorgan dysfunction. RNA sequence analysis revealed that the virus was a newly identified member of the genus _Phlebovirus_ in the family _Bunyaviridae_ . Electron-microscopical examination revealed virions with the morphologic characteristics of a bunyavirus. The presence of the virus was confirmed in 171 patients with SFTS from 6 provinces by detection of viral RNA, specific antibodies to the virus in blood, or both. Serologic assays showed a virus-specific immune response in all 35 pairs of serum samples collected from patients during the acute and convalescent phases of the illness. It was concluded that this novel phlebovirus was responsible for the life-threatening illness associated with fever and thrombocytopenia in China. Subsequent work indicates that the SFTS virus is widespread in China in both the human population and domestic animals (especially goats) harboring ticks.

The press reports above suggest that the tick-borne SFTS bunyavirus isolated in Japan is a distinct strain of the virus. - Mod.CP]
